# Global Phrasing & Style Rules

## 1. No Emojis
- Do not output or write any emojis in user interfaces, error messages, backend api responses, or documentation files (such as README) unless explicitly requested.

## 2. Eliminate Fluff and Promotional Terms
- Avoid marketing fluff and boastful language. Examples to avoid: "生产级", "金丝雀", "智能高可用", "100%", "perfect", "highly-optimized", "self-healing", "zero-downtime", "enterprise-grade".
- Keep descriptions, comments, and instructions functional, technical, and objective.

## 3. Single-Sentence Alerts and Explanations
- Keep alerts (`alert`, `confirm`), warnings, guidance, and status prompts strictly limited to a single concise sentence.

## 4. No Absolute or Assured Claims
- Avoid overly absolute, definite, or assured statements. Use neutral, objective, and cautious language (e.g., "typically", "generally", "reduces chance of", instead of "completely guarantees", "absolutely prevents").
